# Since the ".env" file is gitignored, you can use the ".env.example" file to
# build a new ".env" file when you clone the repo. Keep this file up-to-date
# when you add new variables to `.env`.

# This file will be committed to version control, so make sure not to have any
# secrets in it. If you are cloning this repo, create a copy of this file named
# ".env" and populate it with your secrets.

# When adding additional environment variables, the schema in "/src/env.js"
# should be updated accordingly.

# Example:
# SERVERVAR="foo"
# NEXT_PUBLIC_CLIENTVAR="bar"

# Set to "1" to expose the deterministic E2E test interface (window.__lumines)
# and pause the audio-synced auto-loop. Leave unset for normal/production play —
# no test hooks are exposed and auto-gravity + music-synced sweep run normally.
# NEXT_PUBLIC_TEST_MODE="1"

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AUTH / IDENTITY (real pass only — leave unset for the mock/TEST_MODE build)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Sign in with Google persists ONLY {email, chosenUsername}; the leaderboard +
# scores live in Convex. None of the below is needed for local play or tests —
# the in-memory mock backs the username flow + leaderboard offline.
#
# 1) Convex deployment (run `npx convex dev` to create one; the URL is printed):
# NEXT_PUBLIC_CONVEX_URL="https://<your-deployment>.convex.cloud"
#
# 2) NextAuth + Google OAuth client. Create a Web OAuth client at
#    https://console.cloud.google.com/apis/credentials with the redirect URI
#    "<origin>/api/auth/callback/google", then:
# AUTH_SECRET="<openssl rand -base64 32>"
# AUTH_GOOGLE_ID="<google-oauth-client-id>"
# AUTH_GOOGLE_SECRET="<google-oauth-client-secret>"
# NEXTAUTH_URL="https://<deployed-origin>"   # NextAuth v4 base URL
#
# 3) Tell Convex to trust the NextAuth issuer (see convex/auth.config.ts):
# CONVEX_AUTH_ISSUER_DOMAIN="https://<deployed-origin>"
# CONVEX_AUTH_APPLICATION_ID="convex"
#
# 4) Convex Custom-JWT signing key. This app mints its own RS256 JWT (signed with
#    this PRIVATE key) that Convex validates against the PUBLIC key baked into the
#    code (CONVEX_PUBLIC_JWK in src/server/convex-token-constants.ts + the JWKS in
#    convex/auth.config.ts, served at /api/auth/jwks). Store the private key as
#    SINGLE-LINE BASE64 of the PKCS8 PEM — a raw multi-line PEM secret gets mangled
#    by `wrangler secret put` + the OpenNext process.env shim (it read as empty and
#    broke sign-in, 2026-07-01). Generate a fresh keypair with jose:
#      generateKeyPair('RS256',{modulusLength:2048,extractable:true}) ->
#      exportPKCS8(private) -> base64 -> this var; exportJWK(public) -> the code.
#    Regenerate BOTH halves together (private secret + public in code).
# CONVEX_TOKEN_PRIVATE_KEY="<base64 of the PKCS8 PEM>"
